  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Using Official Exchange Rate</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Never exchange money at official rates or use credit cards (which use official rate). Always use blue dollar rate via Western Union, cuevas, or bringing USD cash. The difference is 20-40%.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Getting DNI</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The DNI (national ID) is essential. Without it, you can't sign leases, get proper phone plans, or access the best blue dollar rates. Apply within 30 days of arrival if you have a residence visa.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Bureaucracy</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Argentine paperwork is notoriously complex. Apostilles, translations, and consulate appointments take time. Start the visa process 2-3 months before you want to arrive.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Expecting Stability</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Argentina has economic volatility, inflation, and changing rules. Exchange rates fluctuate. Embrace the chaos or choose a more stable destination.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Learning Spanish</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">While you can survive in English in tourist areas, daily life is much richer with Spanish. Buenos Aires is an excellent place to learn—take classes and practice with locals.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

