  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the blue dollar and how do I use it?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The blue dollar is Argentina's parallel exchange rate, typically 20-40% better than official rates. Access it by: (1) bringing USD cash and exchanging at cuevas (informal exchange houses), (2) using Western Union transfers (best rate, requires DNI), or (3) using certain fintech apps. Never use credit cards or ATMs—they use the terrible official rate.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need a visa to work remotely in Argentina?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Technically, remote work isn't permitted on a tourist visa. Many nomads use tourist status anyway (enforcement is minimal). For legal certainty and DNI access, the Rentista visa is recommended. It requires proof of ~$1,500-2,000/month income.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Argentina safe?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Buenos Aires is generally safe with normal precautions. Petty crime (phone snatching, pickpockets) exists, especially in tourist areas and on subways. Violent crime is rare in areas where expats live (Palermo, Recoleta, Belgrano). Use common sense and you'll be fine.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the best neighborhood in Buenos Aires?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Palermo (especially Palermo Soho and Palermo Hollywood) is the expat hub—trendy, safe, great restaurants and cafes. Recoleta is more upscale and traditional. San Telmo is artsy and affordable. Belgrano is quieter and family-friendly. Most nomads start in Palermo.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Should I get local prepaga or international insurance?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          For stays under 6 months, international insurance (SafetyWing, IMG) is simpler. For longer stays, local prepaga (OSDE, Swiss Medical) offers better value and access to Argentina's excellent private hospital network. You can have both for maximum coverage.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can the Rentista visa lead to permanent residency?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. After 2 years of legal residence on the Rentista visa, you can apply for permanent residency. After 2 years of permanent residency (4 years total), you can apply for citizenship. Argentina allows dual citizenship.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

